Beijing universities put up posters praising him and indirectly criticizing 
those who forced his resignation in 1987 after student demonstrations. Two days 
later, thousands of students march in Beijing and Shanghai, shouting "Long live 
Hu Yaobang!" and "Long live democracy!" (NO PHOTO) APRIL 22 Official funeral 
for Hu held in Great Hall of the People adjacent to Tian An Men Square in 
central Beijing. About 50,000 students confront police in square but later 
leave peacefully. ; Photo, APRIL 24 University students in Beijing begin 
classroom strike to press demands for freedom of press, more money for 
education, an attack on official corruption and party reassessment of Hu. (NO 
PHOTO) APRIL 26 Communist Party newspaper People's Daily publishes major attack 
on protesters, calling them a "handful of people with ulterior motives" who 
"are actually opposed to . . . socialist democracy and are trampling both 
democracy and law." Harsh attack angers students. ; Photo, APRIL 27 More than 
50,000 students, with wide support from ordinary citizens, defy authorities and 
surge past police lines in march to Tian An Men Square. (NO PHOTO) MAY 4 On 
70th anniversary of historic Chinese patriotic movement, students march to 
square as Asian Development Bank meeting opens in Great Hall of the People. 
Crowd in square grows to 100,000. ; Photo, MAY 13 About 1,000 students, later 
to grow to 3,000, begin weeklong hunger strike in square for democracy. Party 
