leave square passes. Gorbachev arrives at Beijing airport as protests continue. 
Welcoming ceremony moved from square to airport. J. LANGEVIN / Sygma (credit 
for May 13 photo); Photo, MAY 16 Gorbachev and Deng Xiaoping meet in Great Hall 
of the People in formal reconciliation between Soviet Union and China. More 
than 250,000 people mass in square and nearby streets as journalists and 
intellectuals join movement. Protests spread to Shanghai and five provincial 
capitals. (NO PHOTO) MAY 17 Zhao appeals for students to leave square. Students 
reject appeal as 1 million people jam central Beijing. Gorbachev cancels plan 
to visit Forbidden City because of protests. (NO PHOTO) MAY 18 Gorbachev visits 
Shanghai on last day of trip. Protests continue in Beijing. Premier Li Peng 
issues stern lecture to student leaders and refuses to discuss their demands. 
(NO PHOTO) MAY 19 A tearful Zhao visits weakened hunger strikers. Li also 
visits strikers briefly. In move just short of martial law, government orders 
troops into Beijing to try to halt demonstrations, but protesters prevent them 
from reaching city center. (NO PHOTO) MAY 20 Martial law imposed in parts of 
Beijing. City appears in open revolt, with students gaining support from other 
sectors of society and roadblocks being set up to stop convoys of troops from 
reaching Tian An Men Square, where tens of thousands remain. Government orders 
American CNN and CBS TV networks to stop live transmissions. ; Photo, MAY 21-23 
Students say they rejected order by Li to leave square or face military action. 
Defying martial law, hundreds of thousands of people remain in square or block 
intersections to prevent troops from reaching area. Vandals splatter paint on 
huge portrait of Mao Tse-tung. ; Photo, MAY 30 Students unveil a 30-foot-tall 
"Goddess of Democracy" in square. Numbers swell again to view statue. ; Photo, 
JUNE 3-4 Thousands of unarmed soldiers move toward square but are thrown back 
in disarray by citizens. Late on June 3 and on into the early morning hours of 
June 4, troops firing into demonstrators smash way into Beijing and Tian An Men 
Square; hundreds, perhaps thousands, of people are killed and thousands more 
are wounded in clashes throughout the city. (NO PHOTO) JUNE 5 "Goddess of 
Democracy"counterrevolutionary rebellion."; Photo, ; ((; ( statue knocked down 
by army tank. New convoy of about 400 military vehicles moves into square, 
firing repeatedly in area and sometimes at bystanders on streets. Residents 
toss firebombs at convoy, and protesters burn at least seven abandoned military 
trucks. Government media blame violence on " In Washington, President Bush 
suspends all arms sales to China and curbs visits between U.S. and Chinese 
military leaders. J. LANGEVIN / Sygma (credit for June 3-4 photo)JUNE 6-7 Major 
U.S. firms begin evacuating American employees from China. Angry workers in 
Shanghai attack and set fire to passenger train that ran down and killed six 
anti-government protesters. Dissident Fang Lizhi and his wife, Li Shuxian, 
given refuge at American Embassy in Beijing, U.S. announces. Rioting reported 
in Chengdu, in central China. Troops reportedly still firing indiscriminately 
at bystanders on streets of Beijing. Photo, JUNE 8 Premier Li resurfaces 
publicly for first time since June 3-4 massacre and praises soldiers for job 
well done. New martial-law rules ban building of barricades, and government 
radio broadcasts telephone hot-line numbers to which citizens are told they can 
report "counterrevolutionaries." Families of U.S. diplomats flock to Beijing 
airport in response to State Department order for them to leave China. NO 
