of rampaging students burning military vehicles during army assault on Tian An 
Men Square, but no scenes of civilians being killed. Photo, JUNE 13 China's 
police put out alert for 21 pro-democracy student leaders, including Wang Dan 
and Wuer Kaixi. Li delivers hard-line speech praising military and saying 
further steps will be taken "to restore order and strike relentless blows at 
counterrevolutionary rebels."; Photo, JUNE 15-16 Death sentences imposed on 
three men accused of burning train in Shanghai on June 6. White House, trying 
to relax tensions, says Bush believes U.S.-China relationship "is an important 
one, and we would like to see it return to normal." Chinese leadership, which 
said only about 200 were killed in June 3-4 assault, and 100 of those were 
soldiers, continues efforts to minimize scale of deaths during assault, saying 
no one was killed in Tian An Men Square itself. NO PHOTO) JUNE 17 Beijing court 
sentences eight people to death for beating soldiers and burning army vehicles 
while trying to stop military assault of June 3-4. Chinese people urged to 
study major speech by Deng Xiaoping on party line. Poll shows Americans' high 
regard for China has plummeted. ; Photo, JUNE 21-22 Three men, including 
brewery worker Xu Guoming (pictured), executed for setting fire to train that 
